Table ai.Proposal {
  Note: '''
AI (or rule-based) proposal of a concrete action, pending or decided —
the canonical record behind the AI proposal list (AI_PROPOSALS.md).

A proposal is a frozen executable payload: the action identifier plus
the exact validated arguments of the call it wants. Terminal rows are
retained — the AI proposal list is where AI-proposed activity and its
human decisions remain visible and queryable (per-proposer track
records, approval and wrong-rates). Records the proposal targets carry a
render projection in their metadata, written and cleared by the same
services that write these rows; this table is the truth.


*table: public.ai_proposal*'''

  id big_auto [note: '''*ID*''', pk, unique, not null]
  action char [note: '''*action*''', not null]
  subject_type char [note: '''*subject type*''', not null]
  subject_key char [note: '''*subject key*''', not null]
  counterpart_key char [note: '''*counterpart key*''', default:`""`, not null]
  payload json [note: '''*payload*''', default:`builtins.dict()`, not null]
  comment text [note: '''*comment*''', not null]
  confidence char [note: '''*confidence*''', default:`""`, not null]
  proposer char [note: '''*proposer*''', not null]
  scan_version integer [note: '''*scan version*''', default:`1`, not null]
  batch_id char [note: '''*batch id*''', default:`""`, not null]
  executor ai.char_proposal_executor [note: '''*executor*''', default:`"service"`, not null]
  precondition json [note: '''*precondition*''', default:`builtins.dict()`, not null]
  input_hash char [note: '''*input hash*''', not null]
  status ai.char_proposal_status [note: '''*status*''', default:`"proposed"`, not null]
  quality ai.char_proposal_quality [note: '''*quality*''', default:`""`, not null]
  created_by char [note: '''*created by*''', not null]
  created_at date_time [note: '''*created at*''', not null]
  decided_by char [note: '''*decided by*''', default:`""`, not null]
  decided_at date_time [note: '''*decided at*''', null]
  executed_log_id big_integer [note: '''*executed log id*''', null]
  undone_by char [note: '''*undone by*''', default:`""`, not null]
  undone_at date_time [note: '''*undone at*''', null]
  undone_log_id big_integer [note: '''*undone log id*''', null]

  indexes {
    (action,subject_key,status) [name: 'ai_proposal_action_76dc26_idx', type: btree]
    (batch_id) [name: 'ai_proposal_batch_id_516e1ed4', type: btree]
    (input_hash) [name: 'ai_proposal_input_hash_f3b3ef03', type: btree]
    (id) [pk, unique, name: 'ai_proposal_pkey', type: btree]
    (status) [name: 'ai_proposal_status_30b02e7e', type: btree]
    (subject_key) [name: 'ai_proposal_subject_key_267cfeca', type: btree]
  }
}


Table auth.Group {
  Note: '''
Groups are a generic way of categorizing users to apply permissions, or
some other label, to those users. A user can belong to any number of
groups.

A user in a group automatically has all the permissions granted to that
group. For example, if the group 'Site editors' has the permission
can_edit_home_page, any user in that group will have that permission.

Beyond permissions, groups are a convenient way to categorize users to
apply some label, or extended functionality, to them. For example, you
could create a group 'Special users', and you could write code that would
do special things to those users -- such as giving them access to a
members-only portion of your site, or sending them members-only email
messages.


*table: public.auth_group*'''

  id auto [note: '''*ID*''', pk, unique, not null]
  name char [note: '''*name*''', unique, not null]

  indexes {
    (name) [unique, name: 'auth_group_name_key', type: btree]
    (id) [pk, unique, name: 'auth_group_pkey', type: btree]
  }
}


Table auth.Permission {
  Note: '''
The permissions system provides a way to assign permissions to specific
users and groups of users.

The permission system is used by the Django admin site, but may also be
useful in your own code. The Django admin site uses permissions as follows:

- The "add" permission limits the user's ability to view the "add" form
and add an object.
- The "change" permission limits a user's ability to view the change
list, view the "change" form and change an object.
- The "delete" permission limits the ability to delete an object.
- The "view" permission limits the ability to view an object.

Permissions are set globally per type of object, not per specific object
instance. It is possible to say "Mary may change news stories," but it's
not currently possible to say "Mary may change news stories, but only the
ones she created herself" or "Mary may only change news stories that have a
certain status or publication date."

The permissions listed above are automatically created for each model.


*table: public.auth_permission*'''

  id auto [note: '''*ID*''', pk, unique, not null]
  name char [note: '''*name*''', not null]
  codename char [note: '''*codename*''', not null]

  indexes {
    (content_type_id,codename) [unique, name: 'auth_permission_content_type_id_codename_01ab375a_uniq', type: btree]
    (id) [pk, unique, name: 'auth_permission_pkey', type: btree]
  }
}
ref: auth.Permission.content_type_id > contenttypes.ContentType.id


Table auth.User {
  Note: '''
Users within the Django authentication system are represented by this
model.

Username and password are required. Other fields are optional.


*table: public.auth_user*'''

  id auto [note: '''*ID*''', pk, unique, not null]
  password char [note: '''*password*''', not null]
  last_login date_time [note: '''*last login*''', null]
  is_superuser boolean [note: '''
*superuser status*
Designates that this user has all permissions without explicitly assigning them.''', default:`False`, not null]
  username char [note: '''
*username*
Required. 150 characters or fewer. Letters, digits and @/./+/-/_ only.''', unique, not null]
  first_name char [note: '''*first name*''', not null]
  last_name char [note: '''*last name*''', not null]
  email email [note: '''*email address*''', not null]
  is_staff boolean [note: '''
*staff status*
Designates whether the user can log into this admin site.''', default:`False`, not null]
  is_active boolean [note: '''
*active*
Designates whether this user should be treated as active. Unselect this instead of deleting accounts.''', default:`True`, not null]
  date_joined date_time [note: '''*date joined*''', default:`django.utils.timezone.now()`, not null]

  indexes {
    (id) [pk, unique, name: 'auth_user_pkey', type: btree]
    (username) [unique, name: 'auth_user_username_key', type: btree]
  }
}


